This is a generalization of the Holder inequality to products. The proof will proceed by induction on the size of the finite set `s`.

First, let's think about the base case. If `s` is a singleton set `{a}`, then the condition `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` becomes `(p a)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`, which implies `p a = q`. The inequality becomes `‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p a]`, which is trivial since `p a = q`.

For the inductive step, assume `s = t ‚ą™ {a}` where `a ‚ąČ t` and `t` is nonempty. The condition `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` becomes `(p a)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą t, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`. By the induction hypothesis, if `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą t, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = r‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` for some `r`, then `‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, f i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[r] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i]`. We need to show `‚ÄĖ(‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, f i) * f a‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ (‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i]) * ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p a]`.

Using the property `‚ÄĖx * y‚ÄĖ = ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ` for normed vector spaces, the left side becomes `‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, f i‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ`. By the induction hypothesis, this is `‚Č§ (‚ąŹ i ‚ąą t, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ) * ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ`. This is exactly the right side.

