    ‚ÄĖf * g‚ÄĖ‚āô_[1] ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p] * ‚ÄĖg‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] := cLpNorm_mul_le _ _ one_ne_zero

/-- **H√∂lder's inequality**, finitary case. -/
lemma cLpNorm_prod_le {őĻ : Type*} {s : Finset őĻ} (hs : s.Nonempty) {p : őĻ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0} (hp : ‚ąÄ i, p i ‚Č† 0)
    (q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0) (hpq : ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, ((p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě) = (q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ) (f : őĻ ‚Üí őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú) :
    ‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, f i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i] := by
  induction hs using Finset.Nonempty.cons_induction generalizing q with
  | singleton => simp_all
  | cons i s hi hs ih =>
  simp_rw [prod_cons]
  rw [sum_cons, ‚Üź inv_inv (‚ąĎ _ ‚ąą _, _)] at hpq
  have : ENNReal.HolderTriple (p i) ‚ÜĎ(‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ q := ‚ü®sorry‚ü©
```

The problem asks to complete the proof for the finitary case of H√∂lder's inequality. The theorem statement is:

```tactics
lemma cLpNorm_prod_le {őĻ : Type*} {s : Finset őĻ} (hs : s.Nonempty) {p : őĻ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0} (hp : ‚ąÄ i, p i ‚Č† 0)
    (q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0) (hpq : ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, ((p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě) = (q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ) (f : őĻ ‚Üí őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú) :
    ‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, f i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i] := by
```

This is a standard result in functional analysis known as the generalized H√∂lder inequality. It states that for a finite set `s`, functions `f_i : őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú`, and weights `p_i : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0` (with `p_i ‚Č† 0`), we have:

‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, f i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i]

where `q` is related to the `p_i` by `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = (q)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`.

In Lean, we can prove this using induction on the nonempty finite set `s`. The base case is when `s` is a singleton. If `s = {i}`, then:

‚ÄĖf_i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf_i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p_i]

which is trivially true because `q = p_i` (since `‚ąĎ_{j‚ąą{i}} (p_j)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = (p_i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`).

For the inductive step, assuming the inequality holds for `s`, we need to prove it for `insert i s` (where `i ‚ąČ s`). The key insight is that:

‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ j ‚ąą insert i s, f j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] = ‚ÄĖf_i * (‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, f j)‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q]

Using the property of norms, we can write:

‚ÄĖf_i * (‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, f j)‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] = ‚ÄĖf_i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q'] * ‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, f j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[r]

where `q'` and `r` are intermediate exponents. By the generalized H√∂lder inequality, we can choose `q' = p_i` and `r = q` (or vice versa), which gives:

‚ÄĖf_i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p_i] * ‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, f j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q]

By the induction hypothesis, `‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, f j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p j]`, so:

‚ÄĖf_i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p_i] * (‚ąŹ j ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p j])

This equals `‚ąŹ j ‚ąą insert i s, ‚ÄĖf j‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p j]`, which completes the inductive step.

Let's complete the proof:

