# Solving the Holder Inequality in Lean 4

We need to complete the proof for `cLpNorm_prod_le`, which is a generalization of Holder's inequality to products of functions. The theorem states that for a finite set `s`, functions `f_i: őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú` and weights `p_i: őĻ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0`, if `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`, then `‚ÄĖ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, f i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] ‚Č§ ‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, ‚ÄĖf i‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p i]`.

This inequality is a direct application of the Holder inequality for products. In the case of functions, the Holder inequality states that for conjugate exponents `p` and `q` (i.e., `1/p + 1/q = 1`), we have `‚ÄĖf * g‚ÄĖ_1 ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ_p * ‚ÄĖg‚ÄĖ_q`.

For a product of functions `‚ąŹ i ‚ąą s, f i`, we can apply the Holder inequality iteratively. If we have weights `p_i` such that `‚ąĎ i ‚ąą s, (p_i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`, then we can use the Holder inequality for each factor `f_i` with weight `p_i` and combine them to get the desired inequality.

