The condition is: `(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + (‚ąĎ x ‚ąą s, (p x)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`
The inductive hypothesis applies when: `‚ąĎ x ‚ąą s, (p x)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` for some `q'`

So we need to show that the condition implies `‚ąĎ x ‚ąą s, (p x)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q'` for some `q'`. Let's work through the algebra:

Let `S = ‚ąĎ x ‚ąą s, (p x)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`. The condition is `(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + S‚ĀĽ¬Ļ‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`.
This is `(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + (1/S)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`
Which is `(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + S/(S+1) = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`

To clear denominators, multiply by `S+1`:
`(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ(S+1) + S = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ(S+1)`
`(S+1)/(p i) + S = (S+1)/q`

Multiply by `pq`:
`q(S+1) + pqS = p(S+1)`
`qS + q + pqS = pS + p`
`q + pqS = p`

This is `q = p - pqS`
Or `q = p(1 - qS)`

This doesn't immediately give us `S = q'`. Let's try another approach.

The condition is `(p i)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ + S‚ĀĽ¬Ļ‚ĀĽ¬Ļ = q‚ĀĽ¬Ļ`.
This is equivalent to `1/(p i) + 1/(S‚ĀĽ¬Ļ) = 1/q`
Or `1/p i + S = 1/q`
So `q = 1/(1/p i + S)`
Or `q = 1/(1/p i + S) = 1/((1 + p i * S)/p i) = p i/(1 + p i * S)`

So we have `q = p i/(1 + p i * S)`.
The inductive hypothesis applies when the sum equals `q'`:
`S = q'`
So we need to show that `S = q'` where `q' = p i/(1 + p i * S)`.
